        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "which is precisely the desired determinant.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5582706897543613,
          0.06969246022945051,
          0.8383458609348612,
          0.08139534877120189
        ],
        "order": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2002_Solutions_2002s_page_004_14",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Note: a simpler conceptual proof is as follows. (Everything in this paragraph will be modulo p.) Note that for any integers a,b,c, the column vector lax + by + cz, (ax + by + cz)\", (ax + by + cz) '| is a linear combination of the columns of the given matrix. Thus ax + by + cz divides the determinant. In particular, all of the factors of (3) divide the determinant; since both (3) and the determinant have degree p? + p + 1, they agree up to a scalar multiple. Moreover, they have the same coefficient of 2? Px (since this term only appears in the expansion of (3) when you choose the first term in each factor). Thus the determinant is congruent to (3), as desired.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5563388463925522,
          0.0885416666646653,
          0.9210526389119592,
          0.2821930209239716
        ],
        "order": 3
      }
    ]
  },
  {
